1
00:00:00,083 --> 00:00:03,791
When I first entered, they put me in the third solitary cell

2
00:00:04,333 --> 00:00:08,500
I stayed there for two days, then they moved me to another
group cell for about a month, then back to this one

3
00:00:08,875 --> 00:00:12,041
Here I lived the most tragic period of my imprisonment

4
00:00:12,416 --> 00:00:16,000
Because on both sides of me there were women

5
00:00:16,458 --> 00:00:20,916
We could hear the sounds of interrogation and torture

6
00:00:21,583 --> 00:00:26,583
And worse than that, the ventilation opening of the cell

7
00:00:27,041 --> 00:00:30,750
Overlooked the basement and the car garage

8
00:00:31,208 --> 00:00:33,458
So when a prisoner was taken for execution

9
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:35,833
We knew he would be executed before he left

10
00:00:36,250 --> 00:00:41,583
Because they carried digging tools, and we
heard them through the ventilation opening

11
00:00:41,833 --> 00:00:47,583
They placed the prisoner opposite me in the corridor,
asked him some questions, then took him away

12
00:00:48,041 --> 00:00:52,000
They disappeared for two hours or
more and returned without the prisoner

13
00:00:53,458 --> 00:00:57,208
We used to communicate with each
other, as there was a bathroom at the back

14
00:00:58,500 --> 00:01:01,291
We communicated with those to the
right and left. We could hear each other

15
00:01:01,583 --> 00:01:07,541
After the women left, they brought one of my
relatives, Huthaifa al-Hajj Abd, who was later killed

16
00:01:08,041 --> 00:01:12,500
And Faisal Saad Rajoub, a young man from Homs, who was also killed

17
00:01:12,916 --> 00:01:17,458
We eventually gathered in one cell, the sixth solitary cell

18
00:01:18,208 --> 00:01:23,458
It was the most dangerous solitary cell in
the prison, as few people ever came out of it
